Reckoning with it is, to borrow a phrase from an ex-Archbishop of Canterbury, a sacred journey of becoming whole - and takes as long as it takes

@donotcallmemike @J_bagpuss @geeky_gillon @steve_paraprac @ThePinkHairPara @AliceOseman .. when, at the start of Covid and working with covid patients as a volunteer - having half left my previous job and waiting to start my degree - I wrote my will, and decided to come out in it, because I was pretty worried about Covid and didn‚Äôt want to die known as not me!

@donotcallmemike @J_bagpuss @geeky_gillon @steve_paraprac @ThePinkHairPara @AliceOseman .. it then took me several more years and a career change to do something about it because I felt I wouldn‚Äôt be taken seriously, this was something other people do not serious professionals. I‚Äôd been on a GIC waiting list for a long time but finally cracked and was more open..

@donotcallmemike @J_bagpuss @geeky_gillon @steve_paraprac @ThePinkHairPara @AliceOseman I haven‚Äôt really shouted about my experience on Twitter for various reasons but finding words is hard, for me I had a deep discomfort for many years with gender identity but it wasn‚Äôt really until nonbinary identities were visible to me in my early 20s that the pieces clicked ..

@J_bagpuss @geeky_gillon @steve_paraprac @ThePinkHairPara @AliceOseman To an extent but then it comes down to what the norm is around them, for my school norm was homophobia was not acceptable - so while you saw it occasionally, kids themselves pushed back against it. I just wanted to give one slightly hopeful example that it can and has been done

@steve_paraprac @J_bagpuss @geeky_gillon @ThePinkHairPara @AliceOseman Absolutely, it‚Äôs just infuriating to see the same mistakes continuing to be made years later and the same homophobic and transphobic pushback when we know that schools like mine were managing to change the culture around this really quite well 12+ years ago

@J_bagpuss @geeky_gillon @steve_paraprac @ThePinkHairPara @AliceOseman Our school received a bit of grief from the right at the time but we ultimately proved that this stuff doesn‚Äôt have to happen and it‚Äôs down to the school to stop it, it‚Äôs not a natural byproduct of adolescence

The main problem is flow, out of ED to admission or home. It‚Äôs wider NHS capacity and social care, it‚Äôs arranging packages of care and safe ways for people to not be in hospital, it‚Äôs managing chronic conditions in the community. It‚Äôs screwed, so everything before it is screwed.

I had the pleasure of being on the other side a few weeks ago, sent to A&E by an OOH GP because it was the weekend and there was no alternative for the reasonably rapid diagnostics required to confirm what we thought was wrong and rule out something else that could be trouble.

Someone dying next to you in an A&E waiting room would be pretty obvious to external observers, someone dying at home, dying later down the line or suffering long-term harm as a result of delayed 999 service response - often invisible.

When we talk about the current emergency care crisis - A&E is maybe the most obvious because it‚Äôs visibly chaos but the risk and harm is spread invisibly across the community through the knock on impact on ambulance services (stuck at hospital waiting to handover) etc. Bad times. https://t.co/FG6ehhjvBC
